{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"01cf78d3-1206-4883-a638-e06a8b70ffd5","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, so you can use the modern patterns:\n\n**`TestContext` — use constructor injection** (no more static property):\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        // Synchronous init goes here (or in [TestInitialize])\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async per-test initialization\n        await SomeServiceAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Hello from test\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest v3:**\n\n| Concern | Recommendation |\n|---|---|\n| `TestContext` | Constructor injection (not the legacy `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property) |\n| Sync init | Constructor or `[TestInitialize]` method |\n| Async init | `[TestInitialize] public async Task …` (constructors can't be async) |\n| Class-level async | `[ClassInitialize] public static async Task …` |\n\nThe constructor runs first, then `[TestInitialize]`, so put async setup in the initialize method and sync/DI work in the constructor.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"89d3f963-3efe-4d8d-bc18-e7902d4997a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended way to handle initialization is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest v3+, you can inject `TestContext` via constructor injection rather than the old static property pattern.\n\n2. **Synchronous init**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous init**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an `async Task` return type (supported in MSTest v2+ as well).\n\nActually, let me be more precise about MSTest 3.x features:\n\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor (this is the modern MSTest 3.x approach)\n\n\n- Both `[TestInitialize]` and `[ClassInitialize]` support sync and async methods, so I can use `async Task` for either one depending on whether I need per-test or per-class setup.\n\nThe cleanest approach here is constructor injection for `TestContext` combined with an async `[TestInitialize]` method for per-test setup.","outputTokens":603,"requestId":"6805:B29EE:2E97298:333422D:69FD3F24"},"id":"4d8420c9-40a0-44a2-9f0f-cfc023573f93","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:41:05.517Z","parentId":"de9cc674-2a7d-4bff-90ca-a7ab643d37d1"}
